let me know if you can think of a good way to avoid using nargs'}, {'account_id': 17776, 'date': '2015-12-11 00:15:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1

(1 comment)

do we need nargs with default ?

I mean you have already made the default=None, so if pos_tenant_id is passed ( I cannot see a mapping in this code of pos_tenant_id with tenant_id, maybe it is done internally), you will have a value, and if we do not pass anything we would have None .
Can the user pass more than one tenant_id as the positional argument?

( LGTM otherwise)'}, {'account_id': 7787, 'date': '2015-12-11 00:26:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

nargs seems to be necessary to tell it that collecting an item from the CLI is not necessary. The default param just tells what the value is in that case.

https://docs.python.org/2/library/argparse.html#nargs'}, {'account_id': 17776, 'date': '2015-12-11 00:39:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Hi Kevin, 
found the information ...
( Another reference: https://docs.python.org/3/library/argparse.html#default)

We need nargs here because pos_tenant_id is a positional argument.
And I agree that we need positional arguments as given in the bug.... what I am just wondering is if it is possible to accomplish the same with optional arguments'}, {'account_id': 841, 'date': '2015-12-11 06:14:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-12-09 22:57:57.000000000', 'message': "Allow 'neutron quota-show <tenant-id>' syntax

This patch allows tenant_id as a positional argument to the
'neutron quota-show' command. This is helpful because by default
the positional argument is thrown away and the quota is retrieved
for the calling tenant instead, so the user wouldn't even notice
that the wrong quota is being retrieved.

Change-Id: I83d4e0763cc8513a5d608a3754f7d46eaa3f1f6b
Closes-Bug: #1524532
"}, {'created': '2015-12-09 23:27:55.000000000', 'message': "Allow tenant_id positional in quota syntax

This patch allows tenant_id as a positional argument to the
neutron 'quota-show', 'quota-update', and 'quota-delete' command.
This is helpful because by default the positional argument is thrown
away by default and the calling tenant ID is used instead so a user
can unexpectedly update or view the wrong quota.

This syntax is still hidden from the help output to encourage the
more explicit --tenant-id syntax.

Closes-Bug: #1524532
Change-Id: I83d4e0763cc8513a5d608a3754f7d46eaa3f1f6b
"}, {'created': '2015-12-11 06:20:50.000000000', 'message': "Allow tenant_id positional in quota syntax

Change-Id: I83d4e0763cc8513a5d608a3754f7d46eaa3f1f6b
"}]
commit_message:
Allow tenant_id positional in quota syntax

This patch allows tenant_id as a positional argument to the
neutron 'quota-show', 'quota-update', and 'quota-delete' command.
This is helpful because the positional argument is thrown away
by default and the calling tenant ID is used instead so a user
can unexpectedly update or view the wrong quota.

This syntax is still hidden from the help output to encourage the
more explicit --tenant-id syntax.

Closes-Bug: #1524532
Change-Id: I83d4e0763cc8513a5d608a3754f7d46eaa3f1f6b

doc: Add deployment tool integration guide.

Add a guide that captures what needs to be done to integrate OVN and
networking-ovn with an OpenStack deployment tool.

commit_message:
Deprecated tox -downloadcache option removed

Caching is enabled by default from pip version 6.0

More info:
https://testrun.org/tox/latest/config.html#confval-downloadcache=path
https://pip.pypa.io/en/stable/reference/pip_install/#caching

Change-Id: I5376fa4891a1a1f469af36d850b4045d24590aec

[{'created': '2015-12-14 12:08:30.000000000', 'message': 'Always use v3 nova/neutron authentication

commit_message:
Always use v3 nova/neutron authentication

There is no need to test here whether v2 is disabled or not. V3
Authentication will always be available and we should just use that.

This backport is needed as the options used were deprecated in liberty already, and this is breaking grenade jobs.

Change-Id: I0d2d76ebdf261917f1a2b23c65f0f843ae50f49a
(cherry picked from commit 394968fa3d6b0f3b296b49d038aac25b74c2dca7)

commit_message:
Cap tox installation at !=2.3.0 to fix ValueError

Tox 2.3.0 released today and is causing a "ValueError: need more
than 1 value to unpack" when trying to parse tempest's tox.ini.
This is a temporary solution which blacklists Tox 2.3.0 so
stacking does not fail and should be reverted as soon as the fix
for Tox is released.

(Note that this issue only affects individuals and 3rd party CIs
running Devstack and that the gate does not see this problem
since Tox is installed via other means.)

Closes-Bug: #1525352
Change-Id: I46e14b15532b41ff2db2b61ff8ebcf545cb28db6

commit_message:
Switch all ironic jobs to use devstack plugin

Now that the devstack plugin is in Ironic's tree and passing the single
job that was added to test it, remove the temporary job and the
parameter it used, and make everything use the plugin.

Change-Id: I2c52bc014f1b0dbc6b0ae22a4deb4132b4c28621
Depends-On: I147ea059f75720132dd82ff9e7cd3bfdff7fa584

commit_message:
Add reno for release notes management

Adopt reno for release notes like we have done for cinder.
One difference for the client is we will not be backporting
to Liberty per recommendation here [1].

[1] http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-November/080694.html

Change-Id: Icb2520cfa249d104674eb42b5ac93a50a6ce34b4

commit_message:
Set swift_partition to /var/lib/glance/node by default

We should use /var/lib/glance/node as swift partition
by default as it was before and provide access
to this folder for swift user.
Also noop tests were added to cover this parameter.

Closes-bug: #1508482
Change-Id: I928a87c0ad623f4d5a5dbcaaf8a71e3290d68d01
(cherry picked from commit 77316ef2849437cc2842bd7ddf1322841524dbc2)

commit_message:
Manual sync with global-requirements

Since we're not part of global-requirements sync, do a manual sync.
This updates Jinja to newer version as well as normalizes the entries.

commit_message:
update api_samples code to use better variables

_api_version and request_api_version are pretty confusing
semantically. Update these to more meaningful names to make the code
easier to understand: api_major_version, microversion.

Change-Id: Ief6b12fc755a6c48cbef7b82ba226e47850c0b9e

commit_message:
Enable SSH access for ansible-role-jobs

Here we are generating SSH keys for the jenkins user. This give the
ability for Ansible to SSH to localhost to provision functional tests.

We do not want to use root hence the reason for not using the existing
macro.

Change-Id: I2c0283c7547cfd1c98b8cc6bbafbe4a75f2b98bb
Signed-off-by: Paul Belanger <pabelanger@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Make install-distro-packages.sh configurable

Allow the calling environment to override the default paths to the
bindep entrypoint and to the packages list.

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-12-14 16:37:50.000000000', 'message': 'Speed up release-critical post jobs

To finalize the release process for a deliverable, we publish an
announcement pointing to the releases website (docs.o.o/releases).

We therefore need the openstack/releases publish-release-history
job to complete relatively quickly. However with the current
precedence=low on the "post" pipeline, this usually takes several
hours to complete, making this (by far) the longest step in the
otherwise-fast release process.

This change introduces a specific "release-post" pipeline with
precedence=high to which release-process-critical post jobs can
be assigned. Those jobs are rare enough (and complete fast enough)
so that the impact of that higher precedence on other jobs is
limited.

Change-Id: I2cf6355c4dd41dfd53f75cc4d0238f4b45b8eb9a
'}]
commit_message:
Speed up release-critical post jobs

To finalize the release process for a deliverable, we publish an
announcement pointing to the releases website (docs.o.o/releases).

We therefore need the openstack/releases publish-release-history
job to complete relatively quickly. However with the current
precedence=low on the "post" pipeline, this usually takes several
hours to complete, making this (by far) the longest step in the
otherwise-fast release process.

This change introduces a specific "release-post" pipeline with
precedence=high to which release-process-critical post jobs can
be assigned. Those jobs are rare enough (and complete fast enough)
so that the impact of that higher precedence on other jobs is
limited.

Change-Id: I2cf6355c4dd41dfd53f75cc4d0238f4b45b8eb9a

commit_message:
devstack: Print dmesg after loading modules.

Get the tail of dmesg output after succesfully loading the kernel
modules.  This output is sometimes useful when reviewing devstack logs.
It helps verify that the right version was indeed loaded.

Change-Id: I6fd263f9a2d6bd3177a1b01fe0ac76a54f28debf
Signed-off-by: Russell Bryant <rbryant@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Add Router ha, distributed and routes properties

Explicitly parse the ha, distributed and routes properties
for a Router object based on their definition in the networking
v2 API [1].

[1] http://developer.openstack.org/api-ref-networking-v2-ext.html

Change-Id: I03b9d3313415f18dfc1797286c20d8e15752daf9
Closes-Bug: #1525298

commit_message:
Deprecated tox -downloadcache option removed

Caching is enabled by default from pip version 6.0

More info:
https://testrun.org/tox/latest/config.html#confval-downloadcache=path
https://pip.pypa.io/en/stable/reference/pip_install/#caching

Change-Id: I25b5b1d463060e821bdc15be03100347cc5f4889

3) The tempest community reworks/refactors the CG tests and we break them. But the Gate is green because those tests are not run in the Gate.

I think that I should clarify slightly, the test has to be run in a ci system reporting on tempest. We've always said in the past that this was the gate, an experimental job, or a 3rd party ci system. So that if anyone wants to verify a test that requires an out of gate configuration they could set their ci to report on tempest too. (although if the ci disappeared from voting we'd likely have to remove the test)  That being said no one has ever done this before. The burden of having a voting ci to add and keep a test is kinda high for most people. I also think if someone actually proposed using 3rd party ci for a test submission we'd likely want to discuss it in the community again to see if we really think it's a good idea to do that.

However after that aside, Jordan is correct until there are verifiable results returned on this change set this isn't mergable. Just making the cinder feature work with the lvm driver, or some other way to use it in the gate would be the best choice here."}, {'account_id': 6491, 'date': '2015-12-12 21:54:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

I read Matthew's comments similar to this one "We've always said in the past that this was the gate, an experimental job, or a 3rd party CI system" on a different tempest tests submission too, so I thought it is acceptable to run this on a 3rd party CI, which is VNX CI in our case.

Another choice is to run it against a gate driver.  It is inherited from the LVMVolumeDriver and implemented CG functions for LVM.  It is for testing only:

https://github.com/openstack/cinder/blob/master/cinder/tests/unit/fake_driver.py#L199'}, {'account_id': 14624, 'date': '2015-12-14 02:46:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

commit_message:
Add tempest tests for Consistency Group

This patch adds tempest tests for consistency group API in Cinder.

Closes-Bug: #1522151
Change-Id: If4aca6bdea32c74ce72dc3c216bd805eb0fe7924

commit_message:
[fuel-bootstrap] Remove external call for activate function

 * Switch activate function to use execute calls directly
 * Activate still uses 'docker shell' and 'puppet apply'

Change-Id: Ia725c2ceaa159b8797b420d74dcc7c1caf5fbfcf
Related-bug: #1522066

commit_message:
Remove version from setup.cfg

Per [1] we now want to use the git repository for knowing the version instead
of just trying to modify the setup.cfg file.

[1] http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-November/080692.html

Change-Id: I5a4c890b2a4637f1b676273a2509ab8be9f9f034
Depends-On: Ie869901714a96e1dbb97ca58a5cab792b3c9f61d

commit_message:
Move status counter to stderr

This continues work in I09f352b41527c563a158fdcdbb1b7d5bc878c0da to move
the status counter from stdout to stderr, so it does not disrupt Bandit
output piped to a file.

Change-Id: Ib7268a50ecb1c90ebd834937edbf20390d80d556
Implements: blueprint log-to-stderr

commit_message:
Add support for OpenStack Ironic Inspector actions

This patch adds support for all supported Ironic Inspector v1 API
actions via Mistral.

Some updates are required to python-ironic-inspector-client before
can fully support it in tools/get_action_list.py.

Implements: blueprint ironic-inspector-actions

Change-Id: I28c85a0354dd1880eed36bc4cee5a8051ac9d57b
Depends-On: 61f8de56a77187b87c3ae75c637a3aa9045f0beb

commit_message:
Tweaking logger

This moves the log format string to constants and removes it from
the config file (though it can still overridden if desired). This
forms part of the work to remove the config file entirely.

Additionally we now log out to stderr as per the linked blueprint

Implements: log-to-stderr

Change-Id: I09f352b41527c563a158fdcdbb1b7d5bc878c0da

commit_message:
Adding psych on Gemfile explicitly

It seems like bundle has a bug[1] that, somehow, it unloads the psych
library unless is installed through bundle itself. It will be fixed on
bundle 1.2.

[1]: http://github.com/bundler/bundler/issues/2068

Change-Id: Ic2fa8a8f114c3183a656bfdb1bc2d6d6413dbb75

commit_message:
bifurcate for no project id tests

A new noauth3 pipeline is created on v2.1 for a noauth with no
projectid in the urls, and a new scenario is added to test those urls
at the v2.13 microversion.

subject: Fixup our rbac system
revisions:
[{'created': '2015-12-14 16:19:06.000000000', 'message': "Fixup our rbac system

Our rbac system, doesn't allow to filter alarms
by project or user, everything is scoped to the
projcet-id (exception for role that match the
segregation rule). So removed useless rules from
our policy.

This change fixes that.

This also fix the heat gate.

Change-Id: Ic245c76ea3271c7ad826a58b982882cf4ad12ece
Related-bug: #1504495
"}]
commit_message:
Fixup our rbac system

Our rbac system, doesn't allow to filter alarms
by project or user, everything is scoped to the
projcet-id (exception for role that match the
segregation rule). So removed useless rules from
our policy.

This change fixes that.

This also fix the heat gate.

Change-Id: Ic245c76ea3271c7ad826a58b982882cf4ad12ece
Related-bug: #1504495

commit_message:
Grenade jobs for testing libraries (esp. oslo.messaging)

New jobs are designed to pick up oslo.messaging library from
source (and correct branch) and use them during
grenade testing. The existing jobs only pick up oslo.messaging
library from pypi and hence did not work out.

Change-Id: I05e9f18064a82cdd9df08a3b24d5c960c669003e

commit_message:
Allocate separate partition for Horizon uploads

By default horizon firstly uploads image to /tmp directory
and pushes it to glance then. Sometimes a lack of free space
in /tmp dir may cause cluster going offline.

Change-Id: I7cb9edd3f6a31b86696d708c525cf8d031642c58

commit_message:
Argument '--file' should be required

Argument '--file' should be required for command 'openstack-config --upload' and
'openstack-config --download'.
Both v1 and v2 clients fixed.

Change-Id: Iaa1c214b3535857c7d90ab575638a030cebba9c9
Closes-Bug: #1521914

[{'account_id': 19548, 'date': '2015-11-30 14:13:21.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 10068, 'date': '2015-11-30 14:13:31.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

    IRC: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/IRC
    Workflow: http://docs.openstack.org/infra/manual/developers.html
    Commit Messages: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/GitCommitMessages"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-11-30 15:30:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

commit_message:
Deprecated tox -downloadcache option removed

Caching is enabled by default from pip version 6.0

More info:
https://testrun.org/tox/latest/config.html#confval-downloadcache=path
https://pip.pypa.io/en/stable/reference/pip_install/#caching

Change-Id: Ide90df8dd8991a08e4008665a3897d8e51b18996

commit_message:
Tidy up - Watcher Decision Engine package

Some Python class and packages need to be renamed
for a better compliance with the shared terminology
which provides a better understanding of Watcher
objects and components by every contributor.

This patchset is there to change the code structure by adding the folder
"strategies" and "loading".

Partially implements: blueprint glossary-related-refactoring

Change-Id: I56fb24ee6762b3186eccde5983233e17bb227cc1

commit_message:
Remove py26 support

As of mitaka, the infra team won't have the resources available to
reasonably test py26, also the oslo team is dropping py26 support
from their libraries. sine we rely on oslo for a lot of our work,
and depend on infra for our CI, we should drop py26 support too.
Closes-Bug: 1519510
Depends-On: I3ea60260b467710a3e287d88e026f72060f63a1d

Change-Id: I503715ce35d126d18df7f676edb128ba38f4f161

commit_message:
Performance: leverage dict comprehension in PEP-0274

PEP-0274 introduced dict comprehensions to replace dict constructor
with a sequence of length-2 sequences, these are benefits copied
from [1]:
  The dictionary constructor approach has two distinct disadvantages
  from the proposed syntax though.  First, it isn't as legible as a
  dict comprehension.  Second, it forces the programmer to create an
  in-core list object first, which could be expensive.
Manila does not support python 2.6, we can leverage this.
There is deep dive about PEP-0274[2] and basic tests about
performance[3].
Note: This commit doesn't handle dict constructor with kwagrs.
This commit also adds a hacking rule.

[1]http://legacy.python.org/dev/peps/pep-0274/
[2]http://doughellmann.com/2012/11/12/the-performance-impact-of-using
   -dict-instead-of-in-cpython-2-7-2.html
[3]http://paste.openstack.org/show/480757/

Change-Id: I87d26a46ef0d494f92afb1d3bebda2797a12413c
Closes-Bug: #1524771

commit_message:
Add support to boot from UEFI images

Libvirt 1.2.9 version has included support to boot UEFI instances using OVMF,
therefore nova compute needs to be able to boot instances using UEFI images.

bp boot-from-uefi

Co-Authored-By: Ren Qiaowei <qiaowei.ren@intel.com>

Change-Id: I0f1d13ee9c1f81cfe688e174d9e8abce2f4051be

commit_message:
Provide synchronization during the Vopt creation

During concurrent scale deploys sometime we hit the synchronization
issue during the vopt validation.

Change-Id: Ic522b8a1cfc984e114ec74e827ae1546236a7c55
Closes-bug: #1521097
(cherry picked from commit 026f3ad1b10dcdf3986e09b199742984db6ac43f)

commit_message:
Fetch ceph gpg key from more reliable mirror

The ceph master repository is slow and the centos build often fails due
to timeouts fetching the ceph repo GPG key.

Switching to a more reliable mirror should improve things.

Change-Id: I7eef31fa9d83413a7c12134d285b3d20d95805e8
Closes-Bug: 1525505

commit_message:
Add pcmk constraints against haproxy-clone only if applicable

When the Overcloud does not host an instance of haproxy, pcmk will
not have any resource named haproxy-clone so we should not add
any constraint relying on it.

Change-Id: I801f07b7570f3805aa71c22998fec6b6f192b350
(cherry picked from commit f1720b349194d958022d27fd0c5c07e407f55478)

(1 comment)

I get the use case here. The mechanism is a bit clever though in that it rely's on use of the Nova scheduler. I've used the Nova scheduler for the per role stuff with compute capabilities for some time now... and it works great until it doesn't. If it fails you basically have no choice but to enable Debug on your Nova scheduler and read through the log to figure out why the scheduler isn't working.

Rather than end up relying on Nova for more things I would rather see us use direct Ironic properties as hints for this sort of thing. Perhaps this requires Ironic resources in heat that we don't have today... or some other wiring but at some point I'd like to undo some of these things.

---

Regardless I think this should be a useful mechanism for some things until then.

[{'created': '2015-12-08 10:31:49.000000000', 'message': 'Enable per-role SchedulerHints

This adds a parameter for each role, where optional scheduler hints
may be passed to nova.  One potential use-case for this is using
the ComputeCapabilities to pin deployment to a specific node (not
just a specific role/profile mapping to a pool of nodes like we
have currently documented in the ahc-match docs).

This could work as follows:

1. Tag a specific node as "node:controller-0" in Ironic:

ironic node-update <id> replace properties/capabilities='node:controller-0,boot_option:local'

2. Create a heat environment file which uses %index%

parameters:
  ControllerSchedulerHints:
    'capabilities:node': 'controller-%index%'

Change-Id: I79251dde719b4bb5c3b0cce90d0c9d1581ae66f2
'}]
commit_message:
Enable per-role SchedulerHints

This adds a parameter for each role, where optional scheduler hints
may be passed to nova.  One potential use-case for this is using
the ComputeCapabilities to pin deployment to a specific node (not
just a specific role/profile mapping to a pool of nodes like we
have currently documented in the ahc-match docs).

This could work as follows:

1. Tag a specific node as "node:controller-0" in Ironic:

ironic node-update <id> replace properties/capabilities='node:controller-0,boot_option:local'

2. Create a heat environment file which uses %index%

parameters:
  ControllerSchedulerHints:
    'capabilities:node': 'controller-%index%'

Change-Id: I79251dde719b4bb5c3b0cce90d0c9d1581ae66f2

commit_message:
- WIP - test removal of dupes in a migration

In https://review.openstack.org/#/c/212908/19,
we'd like to run a simple SELECT against a table
in order to find duplicates.   The statement timed out
on one particular build server for unknown reasons.
This change is attempting to see if simply ensuring
that the session is committed was the issue.

Change-Id: I4c8e90a0edadea5d83bef1956133c7637ca98663

[{'created': '2015-12-11 21:32:56.000000000', 'message': 'Stack API improvements

The exception that would be raised from list_stacks() if it failed
would not have any type of error message (except the inner exception).
This could be confusing, so add some text that indicates where the
exception is being thrown. Unit tests for this method are added.

Also improve some comments in delete_stack() and add unit tests
for this method.

Change-Id: I979a2948938fc73b708c26d81599061bac7681d4
'}]
commit_message:
Stack API improvements

The exception that would be raised from list_stacks() if it failed
would not have any type of error message (except the inner exception).
This could be confusing, so add some text that indicates where the
exception is being thrown. Unit tests for this method are added.

Also improve some comments in delete_stack() and add unit tests
for this method.

Change-Id: I979a2948938fc73b708c26d81599061bac7681d4

commit_message:
Fixing astute log location for systemd

The correct log location for astute is /var/log/astute/astute.log. This
change fixes the regression which also fixes the missing logs via the
UI.

Change-Id: I176d20a5767b35dd5262afc1ceb212001a2b5c87
Closes-Bug: #1524952

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-11-03 10:09:23.000000000', 'message': 'devref: Rolling upgrade mechanism for rpc-callbacks

Versioned Object push notifications requires the server to be aware
of supported versions in the agents, since they are subscribed
to neutron-vo-<resource-type>-<version-number>.

During upgrade time, the server would need to downgrade and serialize
the objects across the version bracked, and send it to the fanout
queues for agent consumption.

One manual solution could be manual admin pinning, but we can do
better than that, making administrator lives easier if we provide
a reliable mechanism for remote version auto discovery.

Change-Id: I02b694137eb2d58e5f2f3e7631f0e4b90f7c17ad

commit_message:
devref: Rolling upgrade mechanism for rpc-callbacks

Versioned Object push notifications require the server to be aware
of supported versions in the agents, since they are subscribed
to neutron-vo-<resource-type>-<version-number>.

During upgrade time, the server would need to downgrade and serialize
the objects across version subset, and send it to the fanout
queues for agent consumption.

One manual solution could be manual admin pinning, but we can do
better than that, making administrator lives easier if we provide
a reliable mechanism for remote version auto discovery.

Change-Id: I02b694137eb2d58e5f2f3e7631f0e4b90f7c17ad

so, best as i can tell looking around the oslo-incubator code. The base.py isn't pretty but is fairly similar to what clients use, as is utils.py

Is the revival of a common client library here a need someone has or just seems like a good idea?"}, {'account_id': 9107, 'date': '2015-11-10 11:33:52.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2

I'm ok for the global plan, but we need probably to rework the API before a first public release. I don't think that the rework should block this spec, it can be done later. What do you think?"}, {'account_id': 1669, 'date': '2015-11-10 13:33:33.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Let's not spend more time on this and not let it block the work to have a library for request ID support."}, {'account_id': 8276, 'date': '2015-11-11 09:16:14.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Hi Abhishek:

I found a bug in oslo-incubator apiclient, it's not resolved yet, so if we want to graduate oslo.apiclient, can you add it into 'work item' to avoid forgetting?

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/228797/"}, {'account_id': 9107, 'date': '2015-11-11 21:04:02.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

According to the latest discussion on the mailing list, it's not a good idea to graduate apiclient into a new library. There are already cliff, keystoneauth, but also openstacksdk (which might be used in a far future).

Since apiclient has just been removed from Oslo Incubator (change I2020d73fa9cedb3b3b87c1d8dbc8d437857ec7c2), I suggest to reject this spec.

But, hey, it doesn't mean that you should throw all your good work! We still need to work on clients to move apiclient and cliutils.py into their own module (ex: move novaclient/openstack/common/cliutils.py to novaclient/cliutils.py), enhance cliff with code in apiclient and cliutils.py, and then slowly remove completly apiclient and cliutils.py in clients."}, {'account_id': 5638, 'date': '2015-11-12 02:18:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Code-Review'}, {'account_id': 5638, 'date': '2015-11-12 02:22:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

So looks like the consensus is to not do a library...

http://markmail.org/message/m2xefequ7z5hxneg
http://markmail.org/message/w5hqjxhkc2xpcq2i'}, {'account_id': 1011, 'date': '2015-11-12 02:41:14.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

If everyone is in agreement to use cliff + keystoneauth in all clients in near future, then we can start exploring how request id support can be added to the cliff library. IMO, that's the right direction too.

Should we mark this spec as abandon then?"}, {'account_id': 5638, 'date': '2015-11-12 03:02:00.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Tushar, thanks for all the hard work so far. Let's give it a couple of more days"}, {'account_id': 9107, 'date': '2015-11-12 08:33:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

"If everyone is in agreement to use cliff + keystoneauth in all clients in near future, then we can start exploring how request id support can be added to the cliff library. IMO, that's the right direction too."

The idea is to abandon all efforts to enhance clients, but simply to contribute to cliff+keystoneauth instead of contributing to apiclient+cliutils.py.'}, {'account_id': 6159, 'date': '2015-11-12 18:58:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1'}, {'account_id': 6159, 'date': '2015-11-12 18:59:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

ops, sent a review w/o comments. Sorry.

I agree that keystoneauth1 + cliff is the way to go for now. We should encourage more client libraries to move down that road if they need something like apiclient'}, {'account_id': 7191, 'date': '2015-11-13 00:32:16.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

So I think as always there is a confusion here between a library and a CLI. This is obviously part of the history of these being almost indistinguishable in openstack projects. 

As far as the CLI goes I want to provide no help in standardizing all the individual CLIs. I have a spec up to openstack-specs for pretty much that: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/243348/ I would as strongly as possible -1 any attempt to make cliff (et al) a requirement of what should be a library.

What remains though is all the manager code. I personally don't like it but it is fairly standard across clients. My understanding is this is also what Abhishek cares most about because he wants access to the request-id in a standard way. I have no issue with extracting this into a library, i just feel that the code is really horrible and i don't know i want to make it a standard.

There is also a somewhat base client class for using keystoneauth - but this is approx 15 lines and i'd be ok with supporting this from keystoneauth if an apiclient library doesn't happen.

With keystoneauth handling authentication, service catalog etc, openstackclient doing CLI and the SDK coming for users i am less and less convinced that there is any value in the python-*clients at all."}, {'account_id': 5638, 'date': '2015-11-13 02:30:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Workflow-1'}, {'account_id': 5638, 'date': '2015-12-14 14:46:38.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]

commit_message:
Add image re/deactivate commands

This change allows admins to deactivate and reactivate their
images. Currently this has to be done with the REST api or the
glanceclient.

This change introduces `openstack image deactivate` and `openstack
image reactivate`.

This requires glanceclient 1.2.0.

Depends-On: I2c370c6bf6ff664d94d756cc76aaa983fbdb8869
Change-Id: I44d87831b8c3346b216c3d6fd661df1283135785
Closes-Bug: 1516661

commit_message:
Raise an error when trying to upload config with invalid cluster_id

Check if node is assigned to specified cluster when trying to
upload new configuration. Otherwise fail.

Change-Id: I434b61d3887fbe2b23ae2ddedb41c80b944b2451
Closes-Bug: #1523534

"}, {'created': '2015-11-03 14:38:38.000000000', 'message': "Keystone trusts support

This commit adds new functionality in Glance,
called 'trusts', that are used to prevent token
expiration during long upload.

Several new functions and related utilities to work
with trusts were added to 'common' section:
'create_trust', 'delete_trust' and 'renew_token'.
Trusts will be used only for image uploading, for other
cases no changes are made.

The new upload workflow with trusts:

1. Before upload begins glance creates a trust and
stores it in user context.

2. After upload glance updates existing user's token
in the context with the new one.

3. In the end of the operation glance deletes the
trust.

If keystone server doesn't support trust functionality
then glance automatically returns to the basic workflow
with user token.

Implements bp trust-authentication

Change-Id: I5d84ab1164212861af29cfd5811d5e5e4e2de7d1

commit_message:
Implement trust support for api v1

This commit adds new functionality in Glance v1 api,
called 'trusts', that are used to prevent token
expiration during longtime upload.

The new upload workflow with trusts:

1. Before upload begins glance creates a trust and
stores it in user context.

2. After upload glance updates existing user's token
in the context with the new one.

3. In the end of the operation glance deletes the
trust.

If keystone server doesn't support trust functionality
then glance automatically returns to the basic workflow
with user token.

Implements bp trust-authentication

Change-Id: I5d84ab1164212861af29cfd5811d5e5e4e2de7d1

commit_message:
Return full reload on location change

In few places we have i18n() calls which are run on module load.
I think it's not a good idea to wrap all of them into functions,
so this commit returns back full page reload on changing locale.

Change-Id: I5e9fe9549b7091d4a2d0a68ab9a9bcd4698d264a
Closes-Bug: #1525149

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

commit_message:
EMC VMAX - Fix for randomly selecting a portgroup

Before now the utils function was always returning the first
portgroup in the list.  This fix ensures a port group is
randomly selected from the list, where more than one value
is in the list.

Closes-Bug: #1501919
Change-Id: I49020a192f62bc75bca26ea0d206e9ed7c700195

commit_message:
Remove py26 and py33 support from setup.cfg

This patch remove py26 and py33 support from setup.cfg.
Horizon doesn't support these version of python.

Change-Id: I0b9b6a7e42cf0ad8caf8879eb5d6b342b76e8abc
Closes-Bug: 1525786

commit_message:
Record version on container build

This changes default behaviour of build.py to instad of putting latest
tag on it, it puts current kolla version as found in setup.cfg

Change-Id: I4d6e9a0159c6a5598abd58072594df4204427308
Partially-Implements: blueprint upgrade-nova
Partially-Implements: blueprint record-version

IRR - Implemented for setup-infrastructure

The change removes and points our role requirements to use
the independent repos that are now online.

Please detail what metadata is missing, and what it is used for - this might have impact on other drivers too.'}, {'account_id': 9535, 'date': '2015-12-07 12:56:47.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

I agree with Duncan, I don't see what metadata is missing and why can't his just be added using existing mechanism.

Any driver can export driver specific data that will be stored in the DB together with standard backup data and will be imported back using standard procedure.

Driver just needs to overwrite methods `export_record` and `import_record` from base backup driver class.

I believe the `get_extra_metadata` is basically the same as `export_record`."}, {'account_id': 14724, 'date': '2015-12-07 13:52:13.000000000', 'content': 'Topic implement-get-extra-metadata removed'}, {'account_id': 14724, 'date': '2015-12-14 13:10:15.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]

commit_message:
Implement get_extra_metadata

get_extra_metadata will be implementaed in nfs backup driver.
The modification will support backup import on the replication
destination side for disaster recovery purpose,
and generate a file that will import that metadata when needed

Change-Id: Ie272756e33e10ff1fa7110e8822bd9f264f0579c

commit_message:
Adding multipath-tools package for nova hosts

This fix adds the multipath-tools package to all nova
nodes in order to support iscsi-multipath inside nova.

In order to enable this feature in nova the following override
needs to be configured:

nova_nova_conf_overrides:
  libvirt:
    iscsi_use_multipath: true

DocImpact
Closes-Bug: #1524957

Change-Id: I36da282043ce864c8a1fb69a1ee02e3a273c14e4

commit_message:
Add a type restriction to bgpvpns when creating a router association.

Router associations should only be allowed with bgpvpns that have type L3.
This commit adds a check and will raise a BadRequest exception when the
bgpvpn is not of type L3.

Change-Id: I8b9da298a4e74ceddb764d84d86decb4499febe2
Closes-Bug: 1525863

commit_message:
Pass environment variables of proxy to tox

When a development environment is under a proxy, tox is failed even if
environment variables of the proxy are set.

This patch fixes this problem.
Closes-Bug: #1525115

Change-Id: I271ab2581af08ffe0a345b0b795f8ae733e6cc0a

commit_message:
Fix tunneling support for linuxbridge-agent

When I deploy linuxbridge-agent and enable tunneling,
the configuration of neutron isn't right. It lacks
the whole section [vxlan] to be properly configured.

Change-Id: Ib3bfe0f3445f466f4dbb36f7f0cb0d940114e7f6
Closes-Bug: #1481126
Related-Bug: #1524913
(cherry picked from commit c295bca61fbef22d4816b2db8cec40e924c709c4)

commit_message:
Return wrapper classes with request_ids attribute

Added request_ids attribute to the response body so that the
resulting model has 'request_ids' as a property.

In case of list() api calls GeneratorWithMeta object will be returned
instead of generator object. Similarly  for cases where previously
None was returned now a TupleWithMeta object is returned.

Made provision to eliminate 'request_ids' from output shown to user.

This change is required to return 'request_id' from client to log
request_id mappings of cross projects.

Change-Id: I39fc47c25d028c6183fe673bff80df65deafbc7a
Implements: blueprint return-request-id-to-caller

commit_message:
Set a default timeout for 240 minutes for Heat Updates

This matches the behaviour in python-tripleoclient and helps us
avoid Heat timing out the update.

Change-Id: Iae80be66338f88b85b6df7a45055ea84cb5f47b0

commit_message:
Add Wrapper classes for tuple and generator

Added wrapper classes which are inherited from base data types tuple
and generator. Each of these wrapper classes contains a 'request_ids'
attribute which will be populated with a 'x-openstack-request_id'
received in a header from a response body.

This change is required to return 'request_id' from client to log
request_id mappings of cross projects.

Change-Id: If44e3f1bba2113ab26dd56fc95d2411aa78c97e2
Implements: blueprint return-request-id-to-caller

[{'created': '2015-11-06 15:14:16.000000000', 'message': "Fix pinning rules so a package from main can override the one from universe

Current pinning rules don't match packages from the `universe' section.
As a result a customized MOS package (which always resides in the `main'
section) has lower priority than its Ubuntu counterpart:

 # apt-cache policy ohai
 ohai:
   Installed: (none)
   Candidate: 6.14.0-2
   Version table:
      6.14.0-2 0
         500 http://10.20.0.1/mirror/ubuntu/ trusty/universe amd64 Packages
      6.14.0-2~u14.04+mos1 0
         500 http://10.20.0.2:8080/2015.1.0-7.0/ubuntu/x86_64/ mos7.0/main amd64 Packages

As a result the original version of package (shipped with Ubuntu) gets
installed into the IBP image which might reintroduce bugs fixed by
patched packages and/or break features which require customized
packages.

(cherry picked from commit bf324e8f3981b050e89f710ab64411ef0d60ff04)

Closes-Bug: #1488844
Change-Id: I655b34bf0de80d26ba3f8c25fbb6b17bbaefc076
"}]
commit_message:
Fix pinning rules so a package from main can override the one from universe

Current pinning rules don't match packages from the `universe' section.
As a result a customized MOS package (which always resides in the `main'
section) has lower priority than its Ubuntu counterpart:

 # apt-cache policy ohai
 ohai:
   Installed: (none)
   Candidate: 6.14.0-2
   Version table:
      6.14.0-2 0
         500 http://10.20.0.1/mirror/ubuntu/ trusty/universe amd64 Packages
      6.14.0-2~u14.04+mos1 0
         500 http://10.20.0.2:8080/2015.1.0-7.0/ubuntu/x86_64/ mos7.0/main amd64 Packages

As a result the original version of package (shipped with Ubuntu) gets
installed into the IBP image which might reintroduce bugs fixed by
patched packages and/or break features which require customized
packages.

(cherry picked from commit bf324e8f3981b050e89f710ab64411ef0d60ff04)

Closes-Bug: #1488844
Change-Id: I655b34bf0de80d26ba3f8c25fbb6b17bbaefc076

commit_message:
Fixed connection_limit and added UT

Due to a typo, the REST API attribute of connection_limit was
not accessed when creating a new lbaas-V2 listener.
This patch fixes the typo, so that the connection_limit can
be initialized when listener is created. Also, the previous
code did not have UT for connection_limit when the listener
was created. The same has been added here.

Closes-Bug: #1515112

Change-Id: I71eef7b92de91edc1f3ce48f40c645bca704427d

This is a good patch. and I suggest to improve it as follows:
I think that by default only r is really needed.
I assume that the reason you wrote rw is because this is the default permission that the fie would get if the user did not specify the permission header at all. I hence suggest to also modify https://github.com/openstack/storlets/blob/master/Engine/swift/storlet_gateway/storlet_docker_gateway.py Lines 481, 482:
 
if expected_perm != '':
    os.chmod(cache_target_path, int(expected_perm, 8))
+ else:
+     os.chmod(cache_target_path, int('0444', 8))

I think it is best to be as restrictive as possible."}, {'account_id': 9816, 'date': '2015-12-14 01:07:29.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

@Eran Thank you for your comment. It is a good idea to set default restrictive permission.  

I think we still need w because without w, storlet_middleware cannot overwrite that dependency file when we update it(swift user can't write that file with 4xx). I also think we can restrict access by non-owner (such like 600)."}, {'account_id': 9816, 'date': '2015-12-14 03:25:45.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-12-14 03:45:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

commit_message:
Add the validation about Dependency-Permission

When we set the invalid permission about dependency files,
Storlets fails to handle the dependency.

For example, when we do not allow r+w by owner,
Storlets can never handle the dependency file,
after getting it to the local cache directory in swift nodes

This patch adds the validation process when uploading dependencies,
to prevent users from setting a wrong permission.

Change-Id: I2fbbdb5fb7177f4ff79eaab3d8c2fc0ff22ec6a2

commit_message:
Add bifrost as an option projects in Service overview

There is a 'Service overview ' section in install guide[1]. At the end
of this section, it mentions about the option projects. We'd better
add bifrost[2] as an option here so that people can also use ansible
to play with ironic.

[1]http://docs.openstack.org/developer/ironic/deploy/install-guide.html
[2]https://github.com/openstack/bifrost

Change-Id: I2be14b00484c9cef4fb4862fa9514ed60522c1ad
Closes-bug: #1523754

Replace assertEqual(None, *) with assertIsNone in tests

more clear messages in case of failure.

commit_message:
Fix report for task deployment engine

Nodes now update own status: deploying, ready, error.
Progress bar now work again.
Final status of the cluster send after deployment

Change-Id: I694e9afa0e1d9c04b92edf7e72cd406232b24db2
Closes-Bug: #1525388

commit_message:
NetApp: E-Series fix JSONDecodeError on first add

The NetApp E-Series driver would throw a JSONDecodeError on the
addition of a new storage-system. This would occur because a
JSON response was expected, but text/html was being returned as
the Content-Type when a storage-system has been added but is still
coming online.

This patch adds a retry to the driver startup to wait for an array
to come online. It also adds code to avoid the JSONDecodeError
and fail based on the HTTP Response's return code.

Change-Id: I405723039c7a0df10d39bd2eb961ee64d71c2d01

Always use v3 nova/neutron authentication

There is no need to test here whether v2 is disabled or not. V3
Authentication will always be available and we should just use that.

commit_message:
Ironic: Support to install diskimage-builder from source

Prior to this patch devstack only supported installing diskimage-builder
directly from pip. This patch adds support to also install it from git.

This is needed so we can run tests on the diskimage-builder gate to test
against Ironic.

Change-Id: I43ae22dffa704b70f30a4fa7c4d22bc49d66c485

commit_message:
Implementation of router bgpvpn associations.

This commit implements bp router-bgpvpn-association. Router associations
will work similar to network associations except in the bagpipe driver where
the router association will in fact get translated into multiple network
assocations.

Change-Id: Ib1cde80dc22d067f38ab70adeea068ea476bb4c8
Implements: blueprint router-bgpvpn-association

The original implement is OK to me, and from my test, the nodes are deleted by random.'}, {'account_id': 16910, 'date': '2015-12-14 07:35:19.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

1. In _select_candidates function, it first 
calls db_api.node_get_all_by_cluster(context, cluster_id) 
to get the cluster's all nodes, as I kown this nodes are in a list ordered by cluster id. 

2. In random selection, it will always select the first item in 'nodes' list if count = 1, because random.randrange(0) always return 0.
if count = 2, it will always select the first two items in 'nodes' list, because [random.randrange(1), random.randrange(0)] may be [1,0] or [0, 0], 
it always will be the first two items in 'nodes' list because 'nodes.remove(nodes[1]) and nodes.remove(nodes[0])' is same as 'nodes.remove(nodes[0]) and nodes.remove(nodes[0])'."}, {'account_id': 6348, 'date': '2015-12-14 07:57:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2

Your explanation makes sense to me, sorry for the previous review.'}, {'account_id': 8246, 'date': '2015-12-14 07:58:51.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2

Thanks for the clarification. We were mistakenly using 'count' as the number of list but it is only about the number of nodes to be selected."}, {'account_id': 8246, 'date': '2015-12-14 08:01:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

commit_message:
Revise list field read/write

This is a fix to the read/write access to list fields. We need to make
sure we are not doing a lot of operations on such kind of fields. The
data type is not bug-free regarding concurrency.

Change-Id: Id49466fbd34e4d31603a933e551154c644571953

commit_message:
remove py26 support tag in setup.cfg

commit 32397cbd66bc7573e227cb49da1039f137c5f545 removed py26 from
tox.ini, so it's no longer test, we shouldn't claim support for it
in setup.cfg.

Change-Id: I7fbf6b9850914523de0ffb018626f310720c9845

commit_message:
Add new roles to create a router container and custom routes

Add a new role to create a router to pass inter-region traffic.
This change enables the replication bridge interface in the
swift configuration.

Additionally, a role is added to create custom routes, which
can be used to send traffic through the router node.

Change-Id: I4e38b52a25d878359535a0560eaf22fd1ed64056
Partially-Implements: blueprint multi-region-swift

Currently os_cinder manages the file /etc/lvm/lvm.conf. When

commit_message:
Add lvm-setup role and Cinder-specific lvm.conf

Currently os_cinder manages the file /etc/lvm/lvm.conf. When
cinder-volume is deployed on bare-metal this can cause a conflict with
the openstack_hosts role. Essentially there is no guarantee that any
LVM-related activies are due to Cinder.

A new role lvm-setup is added, this is used by both openstack_hosts and
os-cinder-install. This means that the same template is used to create
/etc/lvm/lvm.conf by the different playbooks and the projects use of
overrides means that any changes will be visable wherever the role is
used.

The os_cinder role is updated so that LVM backends use an lvm.conf file
that is located in /etc/cinder. The pv devices used to define the filter
in the conf file have been adjusted to only include those relevant to
Cinder.

Change-Id: Iba2f207bba2f354f32b5f7bf11929a481d1eb792
Closes-bug: 1488532

commit_message:
[WIP] add haproxy ssl termination for openstack public endpoint

This change add support to configure haproxy ssl termination for openstack
public endpoint.
 - nova-api
 - glance-api
 - heat
 - neutron
 - cinder
 - ceilometer

Some of the tests failed in a way that we did not understand. Please help us classify these issues so that they can be part of Elastic Recheck http://status.openstack.org/elastic-recheck/
For more details on this and other bugs, please see http://status.openstack.org/elastic-recheck/'}, {'account_id': 5263, 'date': '2015-12-12 16:49:02.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

This is pointless since upper-constraints (and requirements lists in general) are use _by_ tox (via pip), and so cannot be used to determine what version of tox to use. Our job workers always have the latest version of tox preinstalled, so any alteration to the version used has to happen in the image build process. In this case we've simply rolled back the impacted images and halted further image rebuilds while we wait for tox to address the issue with a newer release."}, {'account_id': 708, 'date': '2015-12-12 19:22:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

It will work in devstack jobs since it will reinstall tox according to upper-constraints (there tox is installed by pip). It will not work for our Python jobs currently, but this can be fixed if we force installation of tox according to upper-constraints there as well.'}, {'account_id': 5263, 'date': '2015-12-12 19:35:44.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

The upper-constraints.txt file is autogenerated. Our automation is not designed to support adding entries to it which are not derived from things either directly or transitively referenced in global-requirements.txt.

You would need this to be part of global-requirements.txt first, and we would need to rework all our jobs to bootstrap tox (and do so respecting the constraints file!) before using tox to install all the actual requirements of the job. I think it's undesirable to further complicate our application of constraints, which is still in its infancy, to address this particular corner case (tox, and presumably other python-based command line tools used in our CI such as pip, virtualenv, bindep, zuul-cloner, ...)."}, {'account_id': 708, 'date': '2015-12-12 20:07:43.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 5263, 'date': '2015-12-12 20:22:29.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

Reregistering my opposition to this, the requirements framework is intended to track and align dependencies of OpenStack projects. It's purpose is in deciding what versions of tools and libraries get installed into the virtual environments where projects are also being installed for testing. Since tox is installed and called outside those environments (it's what drives their construction in most cases), it seems like a misuse of our global requirements system.

I think it's an unintentional side effect that DevStack applies the constraints file to its entirely optional installing of tox, which is simply there to make things more convenient to downstream users who may not have preinstalled tox in their systems and want to run Tempest tests on the resulting deployment. DevStack also optionally installs other Python-based tools (pip and virtualenv, and soon probably bindep as well). I really don't think tox or any of the rest of those tools are relevant to requirements tracking, nor would I want to see our test systems unnecessarily complicated to start applying global requirements and constraints mechanisms to things pip-installed outside the test virtualenvs themselves."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-12-12 21:30:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- gate-requirements-pep8 http://logs.openstack.org/47/256947/2/check/gate-requirements-pep8/8def70d/ : SUCCESS in 28s
- gate-requirements-python27 http://logs.openstack.org/47/256947/2/check/gate-requirements-python27/af59e6e/ : SUCCESS in 38s
- gate-requirements-integration-dsvm http://logs.openstack.org/47/256947/2/check/gate-requirements-integration-dsvm/e3b1f97/ : SUCCESS in 58m 29s
- gate-requirements-integration-dsvm-resolver http://logs.openstack.org/47/256947/2/check/gate-requirements-integration-dsvm-resolver/2d3665c/ : FAILURE in 25m 16s (non-voting)
- gate-requirements-tox-validate http://logs.openstack.org/47/256947/2/check/gate-requirements-tox-validate/dac88af/ : SUCCESS in 34s
- gate-grenade-dsvm-multinode http://logs.openstack.org/47/256947/2/check/gate-grenade-dsvm-multinode/0d6ec1f/ : SUCCESS in 48m 05s'}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2015-12-14 00:08:57.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

So I'm going to -1 this, though I disagree with Jeremy.

Our requirements system is multi-faceted, because people are going to interact with it in multiple ways: making venvs, hacking on openstack, installing system-wide. most projects are pretty good at being installed with other things, so the incremental cost of managing pip, virtualenv and tox would not be deep - and we'd be making it even more explicit what is known to work, and what isn't - and avoiding developer headache.

*however*, we're not ready for that: there are four different sets of test environments (tox, functional tests, devstack, third-party CI) and we'd be affecting all of them by bringing this in. Its a bit of a bug that devstack installs tox differently, because it increases complexity and the difficulty of understanding how our environment.

So - making this change here is premature and won't prevent the problem, but will make it even more confusing when debugging. I'd rather instead see a spec with infra to bring together how to address this systematically - either via upper-constraints, or perhaps image testing + changing devstack... or both? My preference is a constraints based system since I don't really want to have yet another dependency-list-of-python versions mechanism hanging around, but it could perhaps be a separate list from g-r."}, {'account_id': 708, 'date': '2015-12-14 11:21:52.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

OK, I have to agree, such change requires more thinking through.'}]

commit_message:
Add tox to upper-constraints.txt

While being so stable all this time, Tox broke on Tempest's tox.ini with
2.3.0 release. Since it's only installed using upper-constraints from
devstack, this is the only place we can avoid breakage.

For refrence, bug in tox: https://bitbucket.org/hpk42/tox/issues/294

Related-Bug: #1525352
Change-Id: I78f4d4050c6f7eaa1ee27ad3b840e3e94e68a9c1

commit_message:
statsd: fix flush() scheduling

Currently, flush() is scheduled only _once_. Indeed, loop.call_later()
is not "recursive", as it does not reschedule every flush_delay seconds
the call. It only does it once!
So let's build a closure that reschedule itself each time.

Change-Id: I2e16101890996a51cb2baa4ae7b21dd6d1e3c801
(cherry picked from commit 47c4d216b42df997becac229ccd91d0243a37252)

(3 comments)

So you very much need to convince me that we should reinvent this wheel. SAML is a hard protocol and we have already found mistakes between for example shib and mellon implementations. 

What is the problem with shib's n seconds approach? If you want more security lower the seconds, if you want to refresh now touch the config file on the host and shib will reload. I guarantee if we do this people are going to want the n seconds approach anyway. 

Keystone relying on barbican is an unusual loop because barbican authenticates to keystone. Granted barbican generally won't authenticate via SAML but keystone relying on another service is something we've avoided because of these loops. 

Say shib and mellon can't do what you want. Why wouldn't you improve shib/mellon/ipsilon whatever instead? The way I would look to write this is to create a new apache module that implements saml the way you want and plumb it into keystone as per normal. Then you can control it however you like. 

It is really complex to properly configure SAML. It is already too complex to configure keystone. There is no way we should be in the business of writing our own saml providers from scratch."}, {'account_id': 7191, 'date': '2015-11-21 02:40:04.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

commit_message:
Make keystone fully fledged SAML2 Service Provider

Allows the processing of SAML assertions by python code running in 
Keystone instead of depending on the Web server plugin.  Since
mod_mellon or mod_shib are configured per sub-url, adding a new Service
provider means restarting the Apache instances, which would kill all
current connections.  Performing this operation in Python allows dynamic
addition of services.

Change-Id: Ie9f42791238a3dc0c41c8168d2c476f1883eb30e
Implements: bp key-mgmt

commit_message:
Build a Debian IPA image when DIB changes merge

In order to to speed CI build times for bifrost, we will
attempt to pre-build the IPA image when changes have been
committed to diskimage-builder, as the ironic-agent build
element is with-in the diskimage-builder repository.

Change-Id: If9363bff535f9d1fc9692767ac9194923030cfe7

commit_message:
Install puppet-timezone via puppet-modules element

Timezone module is embedded in overcloud images but not in CI.
This commit should fix CI failures in https://review.openstack.org/#/c/249886/

Change-Id: Icf7c681f359e3e48b653ea4648db6a73b532d45e

commit_message:
Correct nova extension check before saving ports

There is no extension with name 'OSInterface' of nova
extensions, correct it to make sure to save external ports
infomation.

Change-Id: I7f5fdc53b56c809ab32f83b207cba582dc833d8f
Closes-Bug: #1515128

commit_message:
Improve public network detection algorithm

It is possible that there are several public networks exist.
ExistingNeutronNetwork used to pick first one of them.
Now when internal network name or ID supplied it tries
to find such public network that the internal network has
a common router with.

Change-Id: I252bb5545891903355cf7f8480a2cd76febcfebe
Closes-Bug: #1524322

commit_message:
Do not assign a value to the class variable 'widget'

Class variable 'widget' stores a default widget for CharField.
It is dangerous to change it. This patch fixes this and assigns
a value to instance variable.

Change-Id: I7220dcacd64aeee096e9340dc49bb4c5ebcfefd5
Closes-Bug: #1521535
(cherry picked from commit 88abc05d2401c1b3e163502923611c7d03c88d35)

commit_message:
Deprecated tox -downloadcache option removed

Caching is enabled by default from pip version 6.0

More info:
https://testrun.org/tox/latest/config.html#confval-downloadcache=path
https://pip.pypa.io/en/stable/reference/pip_install/#caching

Change-Id: I6913f7f385a78218627c0538c2483cd2da2a2ecc

The other thing is that we now need to go through and handle exceptions that we were picking up in our layer prior to this.  Some examples of things that I think this introduces:
http://goo.gl/iL4mvY
http://goo.gl/FxEtNq
http://goo.gl/4v2nSv

commit_message:
Remove eventlet WSGI functionality

This commit removes eventlet WSGI server and starts using
generic eventlet WSGI server from oslo.service library.
The change where the wsgi functionality was added to
oslo.service can be referenced here:
If8840168f10cc3561f4f01e6d456d6b4fd1de8b5.

DocImpact

Depends-on: If8840168f10cc3561f4f01e6d456d6b4fd1de8b5
Implements blueprint: reusing-wsgi-from-oslo.service
Closes-Bug: #1499658

Change-Id: Iea8af7b4a569fedc99e126524f18f98097c95a6d

commit_message:
Tidy up - Rename Base

Some Python class and packages need to be renamed
for a better compliance with the shared terminology
which provides a better understanding of Watcher
objects and components by every contributor.

This patchset add missing Base in class name

Partially implements: blueprint glossary-related-refactoring

Change-Id: I95a3e41fbd5fcd90a99d81c9cf278940f50c7732

commit_message:
Add neutron_ceilometer_enabled default

This patch adds a default for neutron_ceilometer_enabled as it is
missing from the defaults and causing playbook execution failures
when this variable is not set.

Change-Id: I00b432e3e0c6698bc47a05eeaaccddbcc378bfd5

commit_message:
Implement a callback plugin for human readable ansible logs

This implements a callback plugin to make the ansible logs easier
to read. This is especially pertinent for the output of tasks
like shell commands and apt package actions.

It also disables the use of the verbose parameter for Ansible, as
this plugin outputs stdout/stderr anyway.

Change-Id: I56886ba1d7f99b861f625c68078583e82dae2988

commit_message:
Use Ansible AIO playbook for run-aio-build.sh

The new Ansible AIO playbook requires Ansible to be installed *prior*
to running the AIO bootstrap script.

Implements: blueprint convert-aio-bootstrap-to-ansible

Change-Id: I28af8a587bde629fd0c81a6c4ba47dd64c2e44db

commit_message:
Always pass keystone credentials to neutronclient

If the token that is passed to the neutronclient has expired then the
neutronclient will attempt to re-authenticate, when this happens the
current implementation fails because it does not have the required
credentials, this patch changes the _build_client code to pass
the credentials and token to neutronclient and let it decide which to
use.

Change-Id: Icf426a269a41fc941cf95f9c7f279a468dad2400
Closes-Bug: #1524779

commit_message:
Removed H404, H405, H305 ignore in pep8

In the file tox.ini we have some pep8 rules disabled.
We should remove H404,H405,H305 from the ignore list.

Removed them from the ignore list, and got some errors.
I restructured the comments, and now with H404, H405, H305 enabled,
pep8 works without any failures.

Change-Id: Ic2aeb2a8bd47e92fbd2bb0f43fd00d44b6c220ca
Closes-Bug: #1523841

According to the implementation of heat, we didn't remember the previous state before 'check', but we can suspend(in 'CHECK' state) first and then we can do resume. 
I think only remove the check is not good enough."}, {'account_id': 10442, 'date': '2015-10-21 06:10:38.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

Hi huangtianhua,

Thanks for the review.

by allowing the CHECK status it is working fine.

the solution you have proposed will not working in all the case. if your stack is in CHECK FAILED state, you can't suspend again.

suspend is allowing all status except suspend status.

could you please give more info on the problem of allowing CHECK status in resume.

Thanks."}, {'account_id': 10442, 'date': '2015-12-01 06:26:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

any update on this?'}, {'account_id': 6577, 'date': '2015-12-01 11:01:44.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

Masco: I agree with huangtianhua, that current approach will not work for Heat. let's me explain why:
1. we have not really hard dependence between states (except obvious requirements), i.e. you can try to go to some new state in each time.
2. As result you may try to do Stack Check after create/update/suspend/....
3. So when you remove this check you may to come to following situation:
Stack Create -> Stack Check -> Stack Resume
and it will fail, due to Stack was not suspended previously.

Theoretically it may be solved, but inspecting list of previous state, but it needs additional specification for discussion this approach."}, {'account_id': 10442, 'date': '2015-12-14 09:56:44.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

not a correct way of solving this problem.'}]

commit_message:
Not able to resume stacks in check status

Stacks, which are in check status are not able to
resume, since this status is not permitted.

This patch adding the check status in the
allowed status tuple to allow resume.

Change-Id: I378312d8a27b61f19da6444f4fee58a36ce05c66
Closes-Bug: #1506042

Now I can not reproduce glitches with enabling/disabling gateway any more.

Another issue coming up:
Allocation pools are not checked to be within the same subnet. Could you please add a validation for them too?'}, {'account_id': 10442, 'date': '2015-12-09 08:56:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Hello matthias,
this is a partial fix for the bug. for the allocation pool, I will have a word with some neutron guys and submit a another patch for that.

hope this fine.

thanks.'}, {'account_id': 4264, 'date': '2015-12-09 10:01:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+2

Ok, I got you.

The patch fixes a part of the issue, like described in the commit message.'}, {'account_id': 841, 'date': '2015-12-10 11:05:09.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

In the current neutron behavior, the gateway IP must be inside of a given subnet range *by default*. On the other hand, some neutron bug reports mention there is a case where we would like to set a gateway IP address outside of a subnet range. Honestly I am not sure Horizon always enforce this constraint. At least, don't we need to provide a config option?

Note that the bug report I mentioned above is mainly about a subnet on an external network. Thus this change might work, but I am not sure at the moment."}, {'account_id': 4264, 'date': '2015-12-10 12:32:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

@Akihiro how would we reach the gateway, when it's outside of our subnet?

I admit, I am quite annoyed by having to type in everything again after submitting the workflow and neutron finds a typo.

We could have something like a "check" method in neutron to check if a network create would be succesful.
Would really creating the network during form validation be better?'}, {'account_id': 841, 'date': '2015-12-10 13:32:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

There are two cases:
- For IPv4, this thread would be helpful: http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2014-December/thread.html#51855
- For IPv6, a gateway IP with a link local address is valid.
A link local address is outside of a specified subnet but it is a usual configuration.

Regarding "checking" in neutron side, I have no concrete idea at now.
There are several things to be considered. How we can map such request to REST model? Implementing and maintaining such mechanisms can scale or not because a new feature requires extra maintenance cost and we need to asses a balance between merits and costs.'}, {'account_id': 10442, 'date': '2015-12-10 18:03:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

hi akihiro,
thank you so much for the review.
currently if i set the gateway ip not in the subnet range, i am getting error from the neutron.
"Gateway is not valid on subnet". if i want to set the external gateway ip, is anything i need to enable in neutron?'}, {'account_id': 841, 'date': '2015-12-12 23:57:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

force_gateway_on_subnet in neutron.conf defaults to True. Setting this to False allows an IP address out of a specified CIDR range.'}, {'account_id': 10442, 'date': '2015-12-14 07:14:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

akihiro,

got it. thanks.

no way to get the neutron conf detail in horizon right?'}, {'account_id': 841, 'date': '2015-12-14 07:38:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Unfortunately there is no such way..'}, {'account_id': 10442, 'date': '2015-12-14 09:54:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Akihiro,

thanks.'}, {'account_id': 10442, 'date': '2015-12-14 09:55:37.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

currently not possible to implement this since neutron is allowing to set the gateway ip based some config.'}]

commit_message:
Check gateway IP is in given subnet range

In network create form, if we are giving the
gateway IP out of the subnet range, horizon
sending the value to neutron without validating.

This patch validating the gateway IP and showing
the appropriate error message.

Change-Id: Ic1d5cb44ce623f69d1df128fc6e256f103503298
Partial-Bug: #1471685

commit_message:
[mocking-machinery] Add inject YAQL functions

Functions for injecting class methods or objects with mocks are added:
* mock can be provided as method name
* mock can be provided as YAQL expression

* Also, withOriginal function is added.

  withOriginal allows to use data from the original context in mock function.

Targets blueprint mock-context-manager

Depends-On: I9a55d07188ff06bdf98248f011a700c297e33417

Change-Id: Iefee767390209bfad0cca4f39389e0205cd3c9e2

commit_message:
Support assoc subresources with Kilo neutronclient

This change adds monkey-patching of neutronclient.v2_0.client.Client
to get the behavior added by change [1] and fixed by change [2] ; these
changes haven't been backported to python-neutronclient stable/kilo
branch.

This change also adds tests to check that the neutronclient
extension works as expected (from I01f192feadfce99d8eba8ba6701f0139ede985be).

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/202597
[2] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/235827

Change-Id: I5c8f89b1e0b7ca1f6dcad73527964dd5c7120151

commit_message:
Skip gate FS optimization if no secondary disk

This commit removes the assumption that all gate nodes have a secondary
disk, and skip tuning the filesystem if the node doesn't have one.

This fixes gate failures on OVH nodes.

Closes-Bug: #1525047

Change-Id: Ief22f34b32caf7a8b446df888fc5cc1964ad272e

commit_message:
OSWL duplication in DB handled

We can have duplicated OSWLs. They have the same checksum but
different external_ids. Whe should ignore such 'new' OSWLs in the
report generation process.

Change-Id: I71b5ef91eb66a9ce475a78da2485f1ec439acd4e
Closes-Bug: #1524820

commit_message:
Remove deprecated neutron auth options

As a step towards using keystoneauth instead of keystoneclient, remove
the deprecated to-be-removed-in-mitaka neutron auth options so that we
don't have to translate the deprecated code paths to the new library
interface.

bp: keystoneclient-to-keystoneauth

Co-Authored-By: Morgan Fainberg <morgan.fainberg@gmail.com>
Change-Id: I3e3393d99533a70379822178983f73d5eef09bee

commit_message:
Add i18n trans tag for strings in template file

There are some strings in template files can not be translated.
Add 'trans' tags to be translated by i18n module.
The strings include 'Filter', 'All', 'Details', etc.

Closes-Bug: #1525113
Change-Id: I9042bd2b1291a8d542ae871a733587ae256e6263
Signed-off-by: stoneliu <hbjmstone@163.com>

commit_message:
Refactored Watcher codebase to add py34 support

Even though Watcher was mentioning python 3.4 as supported, it
really wasn't the case as all the unit tests were not passing in this
version of Python.

This patchset fixes all the failing tests in Python 3.4 while
keeping Watcher Python 2.7 compatible.

DocImpact
BugImpact
Change-Id: Ie74acc08ef0a2899349a4b419728c89e416a18cb

commit_message:
Fixed an incorrect call to the artifacts client

The artifacts client was called incorrectly in the "toggle public"
call routine, leading to an exception when changing the visibility of
package if using Glare.
This has been fixed.

Change-Id: Ic3da93bde00d96909cae106c358bf4a7d64d19a8
Closes-Bug: #1501374
(cherry picked from commit 9ee3790662c8356d6319d6212bc5b26cecaebb92)

commit_message:
Glare client now properly filters by class name

Adaptor class which wraps the legacy filtering requests into the
Glare-compatible ones has got a conversion for class_name ->
class_definitions attribute.
This fixes a bug when the engine could not properly fetch the package
by class name when deploying an app.

Change-Id: I98846bfad5fc03558dfc2e46fb4dcbfdb40489e8
Closes-bug: #1503224
(cherry picked from commit 4f2336fa382ed18cbdca89bf76eadb213551ada0)

commit_message:
Fixed a download method wrapper in glare adaptor

A method which downloads the package in PackageManagerAdapter class
now returns the full contents of the file instead of the iterator over
this contents.

Although less memory-efficient this is needed to ensure the
compatibility with the legacy murano-api-based package downloader.

Change-Id: I24183f14e70fc6d5a53850d2ac00d5d52fdc5559
Closes-bug: #1521139
(cherry picked from commit dce5e20f9c20ca5c23c72a672d2edd0480fff907)

[{'created': '2015-12-11 15:13:47.000000000', 'message': "'to_dict' method added to PackageWrapper class

PackageWrapper objects, returned by the glare wrapper of the murano
client did not contain the 'to_dict' method which is needed for
carousel.

Appropriate method has been added. It does not need to return the full
dict representation of the object: just id, name and owner_id have to
be returned, as these are the only fields used by the carousel.

Change-Id: I2759ade3cfcbade27b459ba9b21b29e240f7696e
Closes-Bug: #1501405
(cherry picked from commit e5026fff1f958603fb9bf666590f1f2c2961c426)
"}]
commit_message:
'to_dict' method added to PackageWrapper class

PackageWrapper objects, returned by the glare wrapper of the murano
client did not contain the 'to_dict' method which is needed for
carousel.

Appropriate method has been added. It does not need to return the full
dict representation of the object: just id, name and owner_id have to
be returned, as these are the only fields used by the carousel.

Change-Id: I2759ade3cfcbade27b459ba9b21b29e240f7696e
Closes-Bug: #1501405
(cherry picked from commit e5026fff1f958603fb9bf666590f1f2c2961c426)

(1 comment)

See my comment. I also actually don't see a strong correlation between bug description and the change. The bug is about proper error message (which is itself fine, IMO) but the change is about object scopes. BTW, the problem you described in the bug has nothing to do with tenants at all, it's purely a matter of DB object graph integrity."}, {'account_id': 6732, 'date': '2015-12-03 13:36:48.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

I think the root casue of this bug is lack of validation on association with cron-triggers when deleting or updating a workflow, the same with this bug: https://bugs.launchpad.net/mistral/+bug/1518655.

I prefer user can't perform deletion if the association exists, no matter the workflow belongs to the user or not.

I'll also try to solve the problems totally during my implementation of https://blueprints.launchpad.net/mistral/+spec/mistral-resource-sharing"}, {'account_id': 6732, 'date': '2015-12-03 13:37:37.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

and BTW, I don't think specifying scope on cron-trigger will make any sense to users."}, {'account_id': 18238, 'date': '2015-12-04 05:38:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Hi,

Root cause of this problem is while deleting workflow
it cannot be checked whether corn-trigger is exist or not for a workflow because corn-trigger has private scope in different tenant.

So if corn-trigger is created for public workflow, scope of corn-trigger should be public.

This kind of problem is not there if cron-trigger and workflow both are in same tenant.'}, {'account_id': 18238, 'date': '2015-12-08 01:42:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Patch Set 1 was rebased'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-12-08 02:32:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified-1

commit_message:
Get "cron trigger" list using model query.

If cron-trigger is created in different tenant
than workflow's tenant, associated cron-trigger
can not be got. So "model_query" has been used
instead of "secure_query".

Change-Id: Ief78f2cad76e6ca16893bff80c5e75c9015e9c74
Closes-bug: #1522286

commit_message:
Set NeutronMetadataProxySharedSecret

This patch uses the standard password generation functionality to
randomly set the NeutronMetadataProxySharedSecret parameter.

Without this parameter, Neutron has a blank value for it's shared
secret. This value is used to to prevent spoofing, thus the
default value of "unset" is bad. This exposes a potential attack
vector.

Closes-Bug: #1516027
Change-Id: Ifb34b43fdedc55ad220df358c3ccc31e3c2e7c14

Caching is enabled by default from pip version 6.0

More info:
https://testrun.org/tox/latest/config.html#confval-downloadcache=path
https://pip.pypa.io/en/stable/reference/pip_install/#caching

Change-Id: I2f917ca797bcdad8d854440183867a09f7563cdc

Apply offloading props to bond interface

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

    IRC: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/IRC

commit_message:
Optimize the CLI of renaming a category.

The name of the category can't be non-ascii. When no-ascill
characters are used, the program can't find it's ID

Change-Id: I8a886f608b2fceb608898d335114fcde8edb108d
Closes-bug: #1525654

commit_message:
Add oslo_config.Opt support in Ironic config generator

This patch adds oslo_config.Opt base class support in Ironic config
generator so as not to fail when 'auth_type' and 'auth_section' are
generated into [keystone_authtoken] section.

Change-Id: I8c3b95ac3b83154c007e6f77582e2d0f93418a1d
closes-bug: #1522841

Updates to Gateway Device Management spec

Update API and DB models to support Tunnel IPs and
Remote MAC Table management.
Add tenant_id attribute to gateway_device API.
